Definition: [φθείρω] probably strengthened from φθίω (to pine or waste); properly, to shrivel or wither, i.e. to spoil (by any process) or (generally) to ruin (especially figuratively, by moral influences, to deprave)
[φθέγγομαι] probably akin to {{g5338}} and thus to {{g5346}}; to utter a clear sound, i.e. (generally) to proclaim
[φθόγγος] from {{g5350}}; utterance, i.e. a musical note (vocal or instrumental)
[φθινοπωρινός] from derivative of φθίνω  (to wane; akin to the base of {{g5351}}) and {{g3703}} (meaning late autumn); autumnal (as stripped of leaves)
[φθόνος] probably akin to the base of {{g5351}}; ill-will (as detraction), i.e. jealousy (spite)
[φθονέω] from {{g5355}}; to be jealous of
[φιάλη] of uncertain affinity; a broad shallow cup ("phial")
[φθορά] from {{g5351}}; decay, i.e. ruin (spontaneous or inflicted, literally or figuratively)
[Φιλαδέλφεια] from Φιλάδελφος (the same as {{g5361}}), a king of Pergamos; Philadelphia, a place in Asia Minor
[φιλάγαθος] from {{g5384}} and {{g18}}; fond to good, i.e. a promoter of virtue

[φέρω] a primary verb (for which other, and apparently not cognate ones are used in certain tenses only; namely,          οἴω;       and ἐνέγκω; to "bear" or carry (in a very wide application, literally and figuratively, as follows)
[φεύγω] apparently a primary verb; to run away (literally or figuratively); by implication, to shun; by analogy, to vanish
[φειδομένως] adverb from participle of {{g5339}}; abstemiously, i.e. stingily
[φελόνης] by transposition for a derivative probably of {{g5316}} (as showing outside the other garments); a mantle (surtout)
[φημί] properly, the same as the base of {{g5457}} and {{g5316}}; to show or make known one's thoughts, i.e. speak or say Compare {{g3004}}.
[Φῆστος] of Latin derivation; festal; Phestus (i.e. Festus), a Roman
[Φῆλιξ] of Latin origin; happy; Phelix (i.e. Felix), a Roman
[φήμη] from {{g5346}}; a saying, i.e. rumor ("fame")
[φθάνω] apparently a primary verb; to be beforehand, i.e. anticipate or precede; by extension, to have arrived at
[φθαρτός] from {{g5351}}; decayed, i.e. (by implication) perishable
[φιλονεικία] from {{g5380}}; quarrelsomeness, i.e. a dispute
[Φιλόλογος] from {{g5384}} and {{g3056}}; fond of words, i.e. talkative (argumentative, learned, "philological"); Philologus, a Christian
[φιλόθεος] from {{g5384}} and {{g2316}}; fond of God, i.e. pious
[Φίλιππος] from {{g5384}} and {{g2462}}; fond of horses; Philippus, the name of four Israelites
[Φίλιπποι] plural of {{g5376}}; Philippi, a place in Macedonia
[Φιλιππήσιος] from {{g5375}}; a Philippesian (Philippian), i.e. native of Philippi
[φιλία] from {{g5384}}; fondness
[Φίλητος] from {{g5368}}; amiable; Philetus, an opposer of Christianity
[Φιλήμων] from {{g5368}}; friendly; Philemon, a Christian
[φίλημα] from {{g5368}}; a kiss
[φανερόω] from {{g5318}}; to render apparent (literally or figuratively)
[φανερός] from {{g5316}}; shining, i.e. apparent (literally or figuratively); neuter (as adverb) publicly, externally
[φάγω] a primary verb (used as an alternate of {{g2068}} in certain tenses); to eat (literally or figuratively)
[φάγος] from {{g5315}}; a glutton
[Φάλεκ] of Hebrew origin ({{h6389}}); Phalek (i.e. Peleg), a patriarch
[φαίνω] prolongation for the base of {{g5457}}; to lighten (shine), i.e. show (transitive or intransitive, literal or figurative)
[ὕψος] from a derivative of {{g5228}}; elevation, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, (specially), the sky, or (figuratively) dignity
[ὕψιστος] superlative from the base of {{g5311}}; highest, i.e. (masculine singular) the Supreme (God), or (neuter plural) the heavens
[ὕψωμα] from {{g5312}}; an elevated place or thing, i.e. (abstractly) altitude, or (by implication) a barrier (figuratively)
[ὑψόω] from {{g5311}}; to elevate (literally or figuratively)
[φλόξ] from a primary φλέγω (to "flash" or "flame"); a blaze
[φλογίζω] from {{g5395}}; to cause a blaze, i.e. ignite (figuratively, to inflame with passion)
[φλύαρος] from φλύω (to bubble); a garrulous person, i.e. prater
[φλυαρέω] from {{g5397}}; to be a babbler or trifler, i.e. (by implication) to berate idly or mischievously
[φιλόφρων] from {{g5384}} and {{g5424}}; friendly of mind, i.e. kind
[φιλοφρόνως] adverb from {{g5391}}; with friendliness of mind, i.e. kindly
[Φλέγων] active participle of the base of {{g5395}}; blazing; Phlegon, a Christian
[φιμόω] from φιμός (a muzzle); to muzzle
[φοβέω] from {{g5401}}; to frighten, i.e. (passively) to be alarmed; by analogy, to be in awe of, i.e. revere
[φοβερός] from {{g5401}}; frightful, i.e. (objectively) formidable

[φιλέω] from {{g5384}}; to be a friend to (fond of (an individual or an object)), i.e. have affection for (denoting personal attachment, as a matter of sentiment or feeling; while {{g25}} is wider, embracing especially the judgment and the deliberate assent of the will as a matter of principle, duty and propriety: the two thus stand related very much as {{g2309}} and {{g1014}}, or as {{g2372}} and {{g3563}} respectively; the former being chiefly of the heart and the latter of the head); specially, to kiss (as a mark of tenderness)
[φιλήδονος] from {{g5384}} and {{g2237}}; fond of pleasure, i.e. voluptuous
[φιλαδελφία] from {{g5361}}; fraternal affection
[φιλάδελφος] from {{g5384}} and {{g80}}; fond of brethren, i.e. fraternal
[φίλανδρος] from {{g5384}} and {{g435}}; fond of man, i.e. affectionate as a wife
[φιλανθρωπία] from the same as {{g5364}}; fondness of mankind, i.e. benevolence ("philanthropy")
[φιλανθρώπως] adverb from a compound of {{g5384}} and {{g444}}; fondly to man ("philanthropically"), i.e. humanely
[φιλαργυρία] from {{g5366}}; avarice
[φιλάργυρος] from {{g5384}} and {{g696}}; fond of silver (money), i.e. avaricious
[φίλαυτος] from {{g5384}} and {{g846}}; fond of self, i.e. selfish
[ὑψηλός] from {{g5311}}; lofty (in place or character)
[ὑψηλοφρονέω] from a compound of {{g5308}} and {{g5424}}; to be lofty in mind, i.e. arrogant
[ὕστερος] comparative from {{g5259}} (in the sense of behind); later
[ὑφαντός] from ὑφαίνω to weave; woven, i.e. (perhaps) knitted
[ὑστέρησις] from {{g5302}}; a falling short, i.e. (specially), penury
[ὕστερον] neuter of {{g5306}} as adverb; more lately, i.e. eventually
[ὑστερέω] from {{g5306}}; to be later, i.e. (by implication) to be inferior; generally, to fall short (be deficient)
[ὑστέρημα] from {{g5302}}; a deficit; specially, poverty
[ὕσσωπος] of foreign origin ({{h231}}); "hyssop"
[φιλόσοφος] from {{g5384}} and {{g4680}}; fond of wise things, i.e. a "philosopher"
[φιλόστοργος] from {{g5384}} and στοργή (cherishing one's kindred, especially parents or children); fond of natural relatives, i.e. fraternal towards fellow Christian
[φίλος] properly, dear, i.e. a friend; actively, fond, i.e. friendly (still as a noun, an associate, neighbor, etc.)
[φιλοσοφία] from {{g5386}}; "philosophy", i.e. (specially), Jewish sophistry
[φιλόξενος] from {{g5384}} and {{g3581}}; fond of guests, i.e. hospitable
[φιλοπρωτεύω] from a compound of {{g5384}} and {{g4413}}; to be fond of being first, i.e. ambitious of distinction
[φιλόνεικος] from {{g5384}} and νεῖκος (a quarrel; probably akin to {{g3534}}); fond of strife, i.e. disputatious
[φιλονεξία] from {{g5382}}; hospitableness
[φιλότεκνος] from {{g5384}} and {{g5043}}; fond of one's children, i.e. maternal
[φιλοτιμέομαι] middle voice from a compound of {{g5384}} and {{g5092}}; to be fond of honor, i.e. emulous (eager or earnest to do something)
[φείδομαι] of uncertain affinity; to be chary of, i.e. (subjectively) to abstain or (objectively) to treat leniently
[φέγγος] probably akin to the base of {{g5457}} (compare {{g5350}}); brilliancy
[φάρμακος] the same as 5332
[φαρμακεύς] from φάρμακον (a drug, i.e. spell-giving potion); a druggist ("pharmacist") or poisoner, i.e. (by extension) a magician
[φαρμακεία] from {{g5332}}; medication ("pharmacy"), i.e. (by extension) magic (literally or figuratively)
[Φαρισαῖος] of Hebrew origin (compare {{h6567}}); a separatist, i.e. exclusively religious; a Pharisean, i.e. Jewish sectary
[φαῦλος] apparently a primary word; "foul" or "flawy", i.e. (figuratively) wicked
[φάτνη] from πατέομαι (to eat); a crib (for fodder)
[φάσκω] prolongation from the same as {{g5346}}; to assert
[φάσις] from {{g5346}} (not the same as "phase", which is from {{g5316}}); a saying, i.e. report
[φόβητρον] neuter of a derivative of {{g5399}}; a frightening thing, i.e. terrific portent
[φαντάζω] from a derivative of {{g5316}}; to make apparent, i.e. (passively) to appear (neuter participle as noun, a spectacle)
[φαντασία] from a derivative of {{g5324}}; (properly abstract) a (vain) show ("fantasy")
[φάντασμα] from {{g5324}}; (properly concrete) a (mere) show ("phantasm"), i.e. spectre
[φάραγξ] properly, strengthened from the base of {{g4008}} or rather of {{g4486}}; a gap or chasm, i.e. ravine (winter-torrent)
[φανερῶς] adverb from {{g5318}}; plainly, i.e. clearly or publicly
[φανέρωσις] from {{g5319}}; exhibition, i.e. (figuratively) expression, (by extension) a bestowment
[φανός] from {{g5316}}; a lightener, i.e. light; lantern
[Φανουήλ] of Hebrew origin ({{h6439}}); Phanuel (i.e. Penuel), an Israelite
[Φαραώ] of foreign origin ({{h6547}}); Pharao (i.e. Pharoh), an Egyptian king
[Φάρες] of Hebrew origin ({{h6557}}); Phares (i.e. Perets), an Israelite
